          <msContents>
            <summary>
              <p>1 fol. on parchment; Shelfmark: 1993.70; Qurʾānic Text: Q 93:10-95:1; 7 lines per page; Dimensions: 264 x 273mm;  Script style: Large Maġribī <hi rend="italic">mabsūṭ</hi>, angular chrysography (<hi rend="italic">sūra </hi>title); Estimated date of production: First half of 14th century; Provenance: Northwest Africa (Maġrib) or Muslim Iberia (al-Andalus).</p>
              <p> </p>
              <p>  </p>
              <p>A folio from a lavish, multi-volume copy. Yellow/orange dots mark the <hi rend="italic">hamza </hi>above or below <hi rend="italic">alif</hi>, and green dots signal <hi rend="italic">alif al-waṣl</hi>. The symbols of <hi rend="italic">sukūn </hi>and <hi rend="italic">tašdīd </hi>are traced in blue, in contrast with all the other vocalisation marks, which are in red. The same can be said of the angular chrysography used for <hi rend="italic">sūra </hi>titles, with its characteristically long and pointed terminations, is strongly reminiscent of the epigraphy used in Marinid and Nasrid architectural decoration from the first half of the 14th century. Folios from this very manuscript are in:</p>
              <p/>
              <p> </p>
              <p> </p>
              <p>This  is a collection of the fragments under the shelfmark 1993.70, consisting  of <ref target="https://dia.org/collection/qur-folio-49187">1993.70.A</ref> and <ref target="https://dia.org/collection/qur-folio-95416">B</ref>. For further information about the fragments in question, see the linked pages of the Detroit Institute of Arts.</p>
              <p>   </p>
            </summary>
